<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Do &amp; Kajihara" authorityYear="1984" class="Hexanauplia" family="Anthessiidae" genus="Anthessius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Anthessius graciliunguis" order="Cyclopoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="graciliunguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Anthessius graciliunguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Do &amp; Kajihara, 1984 was described originally as an associate of the mussel 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1819" class="Bivalvia" family="Mytilidae" genus="Mytilus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mytilus galloprovincialis" order="Mytilida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="galloprovincialis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mytilus galloprovincialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lamarck, 1819 from Japan (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3147/jsfp.19.5" author="Do, TT" journalOrPublisher="Fish Pathology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="5 - 15" refId="B12" refString="Do, TT, Kajihara, T, 1984. Two poecilostomatoid copepods, Anthessius graciliunguis n. sp. and Modiolicola bifidus Tanaka, 1961 from the blue mussel, Mytilus edulis galloprovincialis Lamarck, in Japan. Fish Pathology 19 (1): 5 - 15, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3147/jsfp.19.5" title="Two poecilostomatoid copepods, Anthessius graciliunguis n. sp. and Modiolicola bifidus Tanaka, 1961 from the blue mussel, Mytilus edulis galloprovincialis Lamarck, in Japan." url="https://doi.org/10.3147/jsfp.19.5" volume="19" year="1984">Do and Kajihara 1984</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Kim, I-H" journalOrPublisher="Ministry of Education, Korea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B27" refString="Kim, I-H, 1998. Illustrated Encyclopedia of Fauna &amp; Flora of Korea. Vol. 38. Cirripedia, Symbiotic Copepoda, Pycnogonida. Ministry of Education, Korea" title="Illustrated Encyclopedia of Fauna &amp; Flora of Korea. Vol. 38. Cirripedia, Symbiotic Copepoda, Pycnogonida." year="1998">Kim (1998</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kim, I-H" journalOrPublisher="Flora and Fauna of Korea, National Institute of Biological Resources, Ministry of Environment, Korea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B31" refString="Kim, I-H, 2010a. Invertebrate fauna of Korea, Vol. 21, No. 5. Symbiotic copepods. Flora and Fauna of Korea, National Institute of Biological Resources, Ministry of Environment, Korea" title="Invertebrate fauna of Korea, Vol. 21, No. 5. Symbiotic copepods." year="2010 a">2010a</bibRefCitation>
) recorded four additional bivalve host species in Korea: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Jay" baseAuthorityYear="1857" class="Bivalvia" family="Pectinidae" genus="Mizuhopecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mizuhopecten yessoensis" order="Pectinida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="yessoensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mizuhopecten yessoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Jay, 1857), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Schroter" baseAuthorityYear="1802" class="Bivalvia" family="Pectinidae" genus="Pecten" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pecten albicans" order="Pectinida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="albicans">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pecten albicans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Schröter">Schroeter</normalizedToken>
, 1802), 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gmelin" baseAuthorityYear="1791" class="Bivalvia" family="Pectinidae" genus="Scaeochlamys" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scaeochlamys squamata" order="Pectinida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="squamata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Scaeochlamys squamata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Gmelin, 1791), and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lischke" baseAuthorityYear="1869" class="Bivalvia" family="Solecurtidae" genus="Solecurtus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Solecurtus divaricatus" order="Cardiida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="divaricatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Solecurtus divaricatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Lischke, 1869) in Korea. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.1.102" author="Ueda, H" journalOrPublisher="Plankton &amp; Benthos Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="102 - 108" refId="B57" refString="Ueda, H, Nagai, H, Hibino, M, Tanaka, M, 2006. Redescription of a symbiotic poecilostomatoid copepod Anthessius graciliunguis Do &amp; Kajihara from plankton: The second record of the species and first record of the male. Plankton &amp; Benthos Research 1 (2): 102 - 108, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.1.102" title="Redescription of a symbiotic poecilostomatoid copepod Anthessius graciliunguis Do &amp; Kajihara from plankton: The second record of the species and first record of the male." url="https://doi.org/10.3800/pbr.1.102" volume="1" year="2006">Ueda et al. (2006)</bibRefCitation>
found this copepod species in plankton samples in Japan. In the present study, this copepod occurred most frequently from 19 of 33 collection sites around the coasts of South Korea. Although we have not examined the Korean population of 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. galloprovincialis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="galloprovincialis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. galloprovincialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for copepods, this mussel seems to be the major host of 
<taxonomicName class="Hexanauplia" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. graciliunguis" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="graciliunguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. graciliunguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, considering that only this mussel inhabits all of those 19 collection sites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The diagnostic morphological features of the female of 
<taxonomicName class="Hexanauplia" genus="A." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="A. graciliunguis" order="Siphonostomatoida" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="graciliunguis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A. graciliunguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are as follows: (1) the caudal ramus is ~ 3.5 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, (2) the terminal segment of antenna is 3.0 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide; (3) the convex outer margin of the distal lash of maxilla is ornamented with five spines; (4) the third exopodal segment of leg 4 is armed with three spines and five setae; and (5) the exopod of leg 5 is 2.1 
